Validacao de schema JSON no Autonomous Database garante consistencia dos dados:

**1. JSON Schema Validation (Oracle 23c+):**
DECLARE
  collection SODA_COLLECTION_T;
  schema_spec CLOB := '{
    "type": "object",
    "required": ["nome", "categoria", "preco"],
    "properties": {
      "nome": {"type": "string", "maxLength": 100},
      "categoria": {"type": "string", "enum": ["eletronicos", "livros", "roupas"]},
      "preco": {"type": "number", "minimum": 0},
      "specs": {
        "type": "object",
        "properties": {
          "cpu": {"type": "string"},
          "ram": {"type": "string"}
        }
      }
    }
  }';
BEGIN
  collection := DBMS_SODA.create_collection(
    name => 'produtos_validados',
    schema => schema_spec
  );
END;
/

**2. Validacao via IS JSON:**
-- Verificar se documento e JSON valido
SELECT *
FROM produtos
WHERE json_document IS NOT JSON;

-- Validar campos obrigatorios
SELECT *
FROM produtos
WHERE json_document.nome IS NULL
   OR json_document.preco IS NULL;

**3. Validacao via PL/SQL:**
CREATE OR REPLACE PROCEDURE validar_documento(
  p_doc IN CLOB
) IS
  v_json JSON_ELEMENT_T;
BEGIN
  v_json := JSON_ELEMENT_T.parse(p_doc);

  IF NOT v_json.get_Object().has('nome') THEN
    RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR(-20001, 'Campo nome e obrigatorio');
  END IF;

  IF NOT v_json.get_Object().has('preco') THEN
    RAISE_APPLICATION_ERROR(-20002, 'Campo preco e obrigatorio');
  END IF;
END;
/

**4. Validacao via Trigger:**
CREATE OR REPLACE TRIGGER trg_validar_produtos
BEFORE INSERT ON produtos
FOR EACH ROW
BEGIN
  validar_documento(:NEW.json_document);
END;
/

**5. Validacao na aplicacao (Python):**
import jsonschema

schema = {
    "type": "object",
    "required": ["nome", "categoria", "preco"],
    "properties": {
        "nome": {"type": "string", "maxLength": 100},
        "categoria": {"type": "string", "enum": ["eletronicos", "livros"]},
        "preco": {"type": "number", "minimum": 0}
    }
}

def validar_e_inserir(doc):
    jsonschema.validate(instance=doc, schema=schema)
    collection.insertOne(doc)

**Boas praticas:**
- Valide no nivel da aplicacao E no banco (defense in depth)
- Use JSON Schema para validacao declarativa
- Triggers para validacao obrigatoria no banco
- [CHECK DOCS] Verifique suporte a JSON Schema na versao do ADB

Referencia: https://docs.oracle.com/en/database/oracle/oracle-database/23/adjsn/json-schema.html

Para configurar lifecycle policies no OCIR:

1. No Console:
   - Developer Services → Containers & Artifacts → Repositories
   - Selecione o repositório → Lifecycle Policies
   - Create Lifecycle Policy

2. Tipos de regras:
   a) Delete por idade:
      - Delete imagens com mais de X dias

   b) Delete por contagem:
      - Manter apenas as N imagens mais recentes

   c) Delete por tag pattern:
      - Delete imagens que match um pattern

3. Via CLI, crie uma policy:
   oci artifacts container repository update \
     --repository-id <repo-ocid> \
     --lifecycle-policy '{
         "rules": [{
             "action": "DELETE",
             "isEnabled": true,
             "filter": {
                 "tagPattern": "*",
                 "timeUnit": "DAYS",
                 "timeAmount": 90
             }
         }]
       }'

4. Exemplo de policy para manter últimas 10 versões:
   {
     "rules": [{
       "action": "DELETE",
       "isEnabled": true,
       "filter": {
         "tagPattern": "*",
         "limit": 10,
         "orderBy": "TIME_CREATED"
       }
     }]
   }

5. Para excluir tags específicas (ex: dev builds):
   {
     "rules": [{
       "action": "DELETE",
       "isEnabled": true,
       "filter": {
         "tagPattern": "dev-*",
         "timeUnit": "DAYS",
         "timeAmount": 7
       }
     }]
   }

6. Para proteger tags de produção:
   # Exclua tudo exceto tags de release:
   {
     "rules": [{
       "action": "DELETE",
       "isEnabled": true,
       "filter": {
         "tagPattern": "*",
         "excludeTagPatterns": ["v*.*.*", "latest"],
         "timeUnit": "DAYS",
         "timeAmount": 30
       }
     }]
   }

7. Verifique políticas existentes:
   oci artifacts container repository get --repository-id <repo-ocid> \
     --query "data.'lifecycle-policy'"

8. Para limpeza manual:
   # Liste imagens antigas:
   oci artifacts container image list \
     --repository-id <repo-ocid> \
     --sort-by TIMECREATED --sort-order ASC

   # Delete imagem específica:
   oci artifacts container image delete --image-id <image-ocid>

9. Boas práticas:
   - Mantenha tags de produção indefinidamente
   - Exclua dev/staging builds após 7-14 dias
   - Use versionamento semântico para fácil identificação
   - Monitore storage usage

Docs: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Registry/Tasks/registrymanaginglifecyclepolicies.htm

Para criar deploy canário com OCI DevOps e Load Balancer:

1. Arquitetura do deploy canário:
   - Load Balancer com dois backend sets:
     - Backend set "stable": versão atual (90% do tráfego)
     - Backend set "canary": nova versão (10% do tráfego)
   - Health checks em ambos os backend sets

2. Pré-requisitos:
   - OKE cluster com aplicação rodando
   - OCI Load Balancer configurado
   - OCI DevOps project

3. Deploy Pipeline com stages:
   {
     "stages": [
       {
         "name": "Deploy Canary",
         "type": "DeployOKE",
         "environmentId": "${OKE_ENV}",
         "helm": {
           "releaseName": "myapp-canary",
           "chartPath": "./charts/myapp",
           "overrides": {
             "image.tag": "${NEW_VERSION}",
             "replicaCount": "1",
             "service.type": "ClusterIP"
           }
         }
       },
       {
         "name": "Add to LB",
         "type": "InvokeFunction",
         "functionId": "<lb-update-function-ocid>",
         "arguments": {
           "action": "add-canary",
           "backendIp": "${CANARY_POD_IP}"
         }
       },
       {
         "name": "Validate Canary",
         "type": "Wait",
         "waitDuration": 300
       },
       {
         "name": "Check Health",
         "type": "InvokeFunction",
         "functionId": "<health-check-function-ocid>"
       },
       {
         "name": "Approval",
         "type": "Approval",
         "message": "Canary looks good? Approve full rollout."
       },
       {
         "name": "Full Rollout",
         "type": "DeployOKE",
         "environmentId": "${OKE_ENV}",
         "helm": {
           "releaseName": "myapp",
           "chartPath": "./charts/myapp",
           "overrides": {
             "image.tag": "${NEW_VERSION}",
             "replicaCount": "3"
           }
         }
       },
       {
         "name": "Remove Canary",
         "type": "DeployOKE",
         "environmentId": "${OKE_ENV}",
         "helm": {
           "releaseName": "myapp-canary",
           "action": "uninstall"
         }
       }
     ]
   }

4. Function para atualizar Load Balancer:
   def handler(ctx, data):
       import oci
       signer = oci.auth.signers.get_resource_principals_signer()
       lb_client = oci.load_balancer.LoadBalancerClient(config={}, signer=signer)

       lb_client.update_backend_set(
           load_balancer_id="<lb-ocid>",
           backend_set_name="canary",
           update_backend_set_details=oci.load_balancer.models.UpdateBackendSetDetails(
               backends=[oci.load_balancer.models.BackendDetails(
                   ip_address=data["backendIp"],
                   port=8080,
                   weight=10
               )]
           )
       )

5. Rollback automático:
   - Se health check falhar, o pipeline para
   - Function de rollback remove canary do LB
   - Helm rollback para versão anterior

6. Métricas para validação:
   - Error rate do canary vs stable
   - Latência p95
   - CPU/Memory usage
   - Custom business metrics

7. Para automatizar a decisão (sem aprovação manual):
   - Use Function para analisar métricas
   - Se error_rate < 1% e latency < threshold → auto-approve
   - Caso contrário → rollback automático

Docs: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/DevOps/Concepts/devopsoverview.htm

Lifecycle policies do GCS não migram automaticamente:

**Mapeamento:**
- GCS Lifecycle Rules → OCI Object Lifecycle Management Policies
- GCS: Multi-region → OCI: Region-specific

**Exemplo GCS:**
```json
{
  "rule": [
    {
      "action": {"type": "SetStorageClass", "storageClass": "NEARLINE"},
      "condition": {"age": 30}
    },
    {
      "action": {"type": "Delete"},
      "condition": {"age": 365}
    }
  ]
}
```

**Equivalente OCI:**
```
oci os object-lifecycle-policy put \
  --bucket-name meu-bucket \
  --name "gcs-migrated-policy" \
  --items '[
    {
      "action": "ARCHIVE",
      "time-amount": 30,
      "time-unit": "DAYS",
      "target": "ARCHIVE",
      "name": "archive-after-30",
      "object-name-filter": {"inclusion-pattern": "*"}
    },
    {
      "action": "DELETE",
      "time-amount": 365,
      "time-unit": "DAYS",
      "name": "delete-after-365",
      "object-name-filter": {"inclusion-pattern": "*"}
    }
  ]'
```

**Tiers OCI:**
- Standard → Infrequent Access → Archive

Referência: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/Object/Tasks/usinglifecyclepolicies.htm

Para integrar OCI Vault com aplicação Java em Compute:

**Passo 1: Configurar Dynamic Group para a instância**
```
ALL {instance.compartment.id = 'ocid1.compartment.oc1..appCompartmentID'}
```

**Passo 2: Policy para acesso ao Vault**
```
Allow dynamic-group AppInstances to read secret-family in compartment security
Allow dynamic-group AppInstances to use vaults in compartment security
```

**Passo 3: Código Java com OCI SDK:**
```java
import com.oracle.bmc.auth.InstancePrincipalsAuthenticationDetailsProvider;
import com.oracle.bmc.secrets.SecretsClient;
import com.oracle.bmc.secrets.requests.GetSecretBundleRequest;
import com.oracle.bmc.secrets.responses.GetSecretBundleResponse;
import java.util.Base64;

public class VaultIntegration {
    public static String getSecret(String secretOcid) {
        // Instance Principal authentication
        InstancePrincipalsAuthenticationDetailsProvider provider =
            InstancePrincipalsAuthenticationDetailsProvider.builder().build();

        SecretsClient client = SecretsClient.builder().build(provider);

        GetSecretBundleRequest request = GetSecretBundleRequest.builder()
            .secretId(secretOcid)
            .build();

        GetSecretBundleResponse response = client.getSecretBundle(request);

        // Decodificar base64
        String content = response.getSecretBundle()
            .getSecretBundleContent().getContent();
        return new String(Base64.getDecoder().decode(content));
    }
}
```

**Passo 4: Dependências Maven:**
```xml
<dependency>
    <groupId>com.oracle.oci.sdk</groupId>
    <artifactId>oci-java-sdk-secrets</artifactId>
    <version>[CHECK DOCS]</version>
</dependency>
```

**Alternativa: Vault Agent sidecar**
Para Kubernetes/OKE, use o Vault Agent como sidecar para injetar secrets como arquivos ou variáveis de ambiente.

Referência: https://docs.oracle.com/en-us/iaas/Content/KeyManagement/Concepts/keyoverview.htm

Criar instância compute:

```hcl
resource "oci_core_instance" "web_server" {
  compartment_id      = var.compartment_ocid
  availability_domain = "QnsQ:US-ASHBURN-AD-1"
  display_name        = "web-server-01"
  shape               = "VM.Standard.E4.Flex"

  shape_config {
    ocpus         = 2
    memory_in_gbs = 16
  }

  source_details {
    source_type = "image"
    source_id   = var.image_ocid
  }

  create_vnic_details {
    subnet_id        = oci_core_subnet.public.id
    assign_public_ip = true
  }

  metadata = {
    ssh_authorized_keys = file("~/.ssh/id_rsa.pub")
  }
}
```

**Shapes:** VM.Standard.E4.Flex (AMD), VM.Standard.A1.Flex (ARM, econômico)

Doc: https://registry.terraform.io/providers/oracle/oci/latest/docs

Instance pool + auto-scaling:

**1. Instance Configuration:**
```hcl
resource "oci_core_instance_configuration" "web_config" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  instance_details {
    instance_type = "compute"
    launch_details {
      shape = "VM.Standard.E4.Flex"
      shape_config { ocpus = 2; memory_in_gbs = 16 }
      create_vnic_details { subnet_id = oci_core_subnet.private.id }
    }
  }
}
```

**2. Instance Pool:**
```hcl
resource "oci_core_instance_pool" "web_pool" {
  compartment_id            = var.compartment_ocid
  instance_configuration_id = oci_core_instance_configuration.web_config.id
  size                      = 2
}
```

**3. Auto Scaling:**
```hcl
resource "oci_autoscaling_auto_scaling_configuration" "web" {
  policies {
    capacity { initial = 2; min = 1; max = 10 }
    rules {
      action { type = "CHANGE_COUNT_BY"; value = 1 }
      trigger { metric { metric_type = "CPU_UTILIZATION" }; threshold { operator = "GT"; value = 80 } }
    }
  }
}
```

Doc: https://registry.terraform.io/providers/oracle/oci/latest/docs

Custom images:

**1. Import de Object Storage:**
```hcl
resource "oci_core_image" "custom" {
  compartment_id = var.compartment_ocid
  display_name   = "custom-ubuntu-22-04"
  image_source_details {
    source_type  = "objectStorageUri"
    source_uri   = "oci://bucket/n/namespace/o/image.qcow2"
    launch_mode  = "PARAVIRTUALIZED"
  }
}
```

**2. De boot volume:**
```hcl
resource "oci_core_image" "from_bv" {
  image_source_details {
    source_type    = "bootVolume"
    boot_volume_id = oci_core_boot_volume.golden.id
    launch_mode    = "PARAVIRTUALIZED"
  }
}
```

**3. Use na instância:** source_id = oci_core_image.custom.id

Doc: https://registry.terraform.io/providers/oracle/oci/latest/docs

Cloud-init via Terraform:

```hcl
